The first test is OK : if the number of books per shelf is less or equal to the size of boxes, the number of the boxes needed is the number of shelves. (please note that the `+` sign has no effect)

The second test is too specific (but not wrong) : if there are no books, no boxes will be needed whatever the size of the boxes.

The problem is when you add one box per shelf (`q = r +1`) whereas it is only needed when the number of the boxes is not a multiple of the boxes size.

Here is a solution : 

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int T = sc.nextInt();
        while (1 &lt;= T &amp;&amp; T-- &lt;= 100) {
            int nbShelves = sc.nextInt();
            int nbBooksPerShelf = sc.nextInt();
            int nbBooksPerBox = sc.nextInt();
            int nbBoxesPerShelf = nbBooksPerShelf / nbBooksPerBox;
            if (nbBooksPerShelf % nbBooksPerBox &gt; 0)
                nbBoxesPerShelf++;

            System.out.println(nbBoxesPerShelf * nbShelves);
        }
    }

